K-means without dimension reduction

library(foreach)
library(doParallel)


num_cores <- detectCores()   # Use one less than the total number of cores
cl <- makeCluster(num_cores)     # Create a cluster
registerDoParallel(cl)            # Register the cluster for parallel processing

start <- Sys.time()              # Record start time
set.seed(42)                     # Set seed for reproducibility

# Run the silhouette score computations in parallel using foreach
sil_scores <- foreach(k = 2:10, .combine = c) %dopar% {
  clustering_modes <- kmeans(x = scaled_log_nutrients[, 1:9], centers = k, iter.max = 50, nstart = 10)
  sil_modes <- cluster::silhouette(clustering_modes$cluster, dist(scaled_log_nutrients[, 1:9], method = 'euclidian'))
  mean(sil_modes[, 'sil_width'])  # Return mean silhouette width
}

stopCluster(cl)                    # Stop the cluster

end <- Sys.time()                  # Record end time
difference <- end - start   
for_plot = data.frame(
  k = seq(2, 10),
  sil_score = sil_scores
)

ggplot(data = for_plot, aes(x = k, y = sil_score)) + geom_line() + theme_classic() +
  ylab("Average Silhouette Width") + xlab("k") + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(2, 11, by = 1)) + geom_point()

# Create a list to store plots for each cluster
category_plots <- list()

# Loop through each unique cluster
for (c in unique(scaled_log_nutrients$cluster)) {
  
  # Filter the data for the current cluster
  cluster_data <- scaled_log_nutrients[scaled_log_nutrients$cluster == c, ]
  
  # Calculate category counts for category_2
  category_counts <- as.data.frame(table(cluster_data$category_2))
  
  # Rename columns for clarity
  names(category_counts) <- c("category", "count")
  
  # Filter for the top 10 most common categories
  top_categories <- category_counts %>%
    arrange(desc(count)) %>%
    head(10)
  
  # Create the plot for the current cluster
  p <- ggplot(data = top_categories, aes(x = reorder(category, count), y = count)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', fill = 'steelblue2') +
    xlab(NULL) +
    ylab('Count') +
    ggtitle(paste('Top 10 Food Categories for Cluster', c)) +
    coord_flip() +
    theme_minimal()
  
  # Store the plot in the list
  category_plots[[as.character(c)]] <- p
}

# To display a plot, you can use print(category_plots[[<cluster_number>]]) for specific clusters,
# or display all at once

  group_by(Cluster) %>%
  mutate(Total = sum(Count)) %>%
  ungroup()

  mutate(Proportion = ifelse(Is_UPF_Marker == "Yes", Count / Total, NA))

  filter(!is.na(Proportion))

# Loop through each unique cluster
for (c in unique(nutrients_additives$cluster)) {
  
  # Filter the data for the current cluster
  cluster_data <- nutrients_additives[nutrients_additives$cluster == c, ]
  
  # Calculate category counts for category_2
  category_counts <- as.data.frame(table(cluster_data$category_2))
  
  # Rename columns for clarity
  names(category_counts) <- c("category", "count")
  
  # Filter for the top 10 most common categories
  top_categories <- category_counts %>%
    arrange(desc(count)) %>%
    head(10)
  
  # Create the plot for the current cluster
  p <- ggplot(data = top_categories, aes(x = reorder(category, count), y = count)) +
    geom_bar(stat = 'identity', fill = 'steelblue2') +
    xlab(NULL) +
    ylab('Count') +
    ggtitle(paste('Top 10 Food Categories for Cluster', c)) +
    coord_flip() +
    theme_minimal()
  
  # Store the plot in the list
  category_plots[[as.character(c)]] <- p
}
